{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's persona in \"Hazaaron khwahishein aisi ke har khwahish pe dam nikle\":**  \n\"A thousand wishes, each could make my spirit cease; / So many of my dreams came true, yet brought so little peace.\"[^1]  \n\n**The Wanderer:**  \n\"The path of exile holds him, not twisted gold, / a frozen spirit-lock, not the earth's splendor.\"[^2]  \n\nBoth speakers would find the other's grief recognizable. The Wanderer, adrift in frozen isolation after losing his lord, kinsmen, and hall-joys—replaced only by wyrd-bound sorrow—would see his own endless lament mirrored in Ghalib's persona, whose countless desires persist unquenched even when some fulfill, leaving a hollow ache. Likewise, Ghalib's voice of insatiable longing would echo the Wanderer's \"cruel companion sorrow,\" where past treasures and comforts haunt as irretrievable, binding the spirit in perpetual winter.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/70-hazaaron-khwahishein-aisi-ke-har-khwahish-pe-dam-n/translation/#p-fcc8ca).  \n[^2]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).  \n[^3]: See full contexts in *Diwan-E-Ghalib* ch. 70 [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/70-hazaaron-khwahishein-aisi-ke-har-khwahish-pe-dam-n/translation/) and *Old English Elegies* ch. 11 [chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/).",
